SUMMARY:McClelland & Stewart Poetry Night 2026
DESCRIPTION:TORONTO ARTS & CULTURE\nWe attend this event every year--learn
 ing more about *Poetry/Prose/Verse!*\n\nThe venue changes each year. This 
 time we'll be at Yonge/Davenport.\n\n**(Nancy and Ed Jackman Performance C
 entre)**\n\nPlease **reserve your own FREE ticket** through Eventbrite lin
 k here:\n\nhttps://www.eventbrite.ca/e/mcclelland-stewart-poetry-night-202
 6-tickets-1983390212517?aff=ebdsoporgprofile\n\nOverview:\nJoin us for McC
 lelland & Stewart Poetry Night 2026\, featuring Laurie D. Graham\, Kaie Ke
 llough\, and Jake Skeets!\n\n**Curated by M&S Poetry Editor\, Canisia Lubr
 in\, who since 2021 has published groundbreaking collections by the bright
 est poets in the country.**\n\nDoors at 6:45 pm\, event starts at 7:15 pm.
  Admission is free and tickets are general admission. Registering for a ti
 cket does not guarantee admission and we recommend arriving early!\n\n**AB
 OUT THE BOOKS & POETS--**\n\nTwo-time Trillium Book Award finalist Laurie 
 D. Graham brings us **CALLING IT BACK TO ME**\, a personal collection of f
 amilial history and memory.\n**LAURIE D. GRAHAM** grew up in Treaty 6 Terr
 itory\, near amiskwacîwâskahikan (Edmonton\, Alberta)\, and she has live
 d in Nogojiwanong/Peterborough\, in the Territory of the Mississauga Anish
 inaabeg\, since 2018\, where she is a poet\, an editor\, and the publisher
  of *Brick* magazine\, a journal of literary non-fiction based in Toronto.
  Her first book\, *Rove*\, was shortlisted for the Gerald Lampert Memorial
  Award for the best first book of poetry in Canada. Her second and third b
 ooks\, *Settler Education* and *Fast Commute*\, were both nominated for On
 tario’s Trillium Book Award for Poetry.\n\nFrom Griffin Prize winner Kai
 e Kellough\, we have **INTERPOSITION**—a long poem that examines desire 
 and technology.\n**KAIE KELLOUGH** is a poet\, fiction writer\, and sound 
 performer living in Montreal. His previous collection\, *Magnetic Equator*
 \, won the 2020 Griffin Poetry Prize. He is a writer and vocalist for the 
 group FYEAR and is pursuing graduate work in English at Queen’s Universi
 ty.\n**HORSES** is Navajo Nation Poet Laureate Jake Skeets' poignant colle
 ction tracking the impacts of climate change on the land and people of the
  Navajo Nation.\n\n**JAKE SKEETS** is the author of *Eyes Bottle Dark with
  a Mouthful of Flowers*\, selected by the National Poetry Series and winne
 r of the Kate Tufts Discovery Award and an American Book Award. A Whiting 
 Award recipient\, Skeets is from the Navajo Nation and was appointed the N
 ation’s third Poet Laureate. He is an assistant professor of English at 
 the University of Oklahoma.\n\nSee you there. A five minute walk north of 
 the Canadian Tire at Yonge/Davenport.
